            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How the line counter works</h2>
              <p>
                This line counter is designed for writers, developers, and
                editors who need accurate line statistics for text or source
                code. It works entirely in your browser and updates in real time
                as you type or paste content.
              </p>
              <p>The tool supports different operating-system line endings:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Unix / Linux / modern macOS:</strong>
                  <code>\n</code> (LF)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Windows:</strong> <code>\r\n</code> (CRLF)</li>
                <li><strong>Old Mac:</strong> <code>\r</code> (CR)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                It normalizes these endings so that counts are consistent, even
                if your file mixes styles (for example, after copy–pasting from
                different editors).
              </p>

              <h3>What each metric means</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total lines:</strong> every line in the text,
                  including blank lines.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Non-empty lines:</strong> lines that contain at least
                  one non-whitespace character after trimming spaces and tabs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Empty lines:</strong> lines that become empty after
                  trimming whitespace.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Characters:</strong> total number of characters,
                  including spaces and line breaks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Characters without spaces:</strong> characters
                  excluding regular spaces and tab characters.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Words:</strong> sequences of non-whitespace characters
                  separated by spaces, tabs, or line breaks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Average line length:</strong> total characters divided
                  by the number of lines (rounded to one decimal place).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Longest line:</strong> the maximum number of
                  characters found on a single line, plus the line number where
                  it occurs.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Basic counting logic</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. Normalize line endings</strong></p>
                <pre class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-xs md:text-sm">
text = text.replace(/\r\n/g, '\n').replace(/\r/g, '\n');</pre
                >
                <p><strong>2. Split into lines</strong></p>
                <pre class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-xs md:text-sm">
const lines = text.split('\n');</pre
                >
                <p><strong>3. Classify each line</strong></p>
                <pre class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-xs md:text-sm">
for each line:
  trimmed = line.trim();
  if (trimmed.length === 0) → empty line
  else → non-empty line</pre
                >
              </div>

              <h2>Common use cases</h2>
              <h3>1. Writers and students</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Check line limits for poetry, scripts, or assignments.</li>
                <li>
                  Ensure each paragraph or bullet list stays within a certain
                  length.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Developers</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Get a quick line-of-code (LOC) estimate for a snippet or
                  single file.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compare non-empty lines vs. total lines to see how much is
                  comments or whitespace.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Inspect log files and configuration files for unexpected blank
                  lines.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Editors and QA</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Verify that content meets line-based formatting requirements.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Check for trailing blank lines or overly long lines that might
                  break layouts.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Tips for accurate results</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Turn on <strong>“Trim whitespace on each line”</strong> to
                  avoid counting lines that only contain spaces or tabs as
                  non-empty.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use
                  <strong>“Ignore lines that are only whitespace”</strong> when
                  you only care about meaningful content lines.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you know your target environment (Windows vs. Unix), set
                  the <strong>Normalize line endings</strong> option explicitly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For very large files, prefer uploading the file instead of
                  pasting to avoid browser slowdowns.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Privacy and security</h2>
              <p>
                This line counter runs entirely on the client side. Your text or
                code never leaves your browser:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>No data is sent to a server for processing.</li>
                <li>No content is stored or logged.</li>
                <li>
                  You can safely use it with sensitive documents or proprietary
                  code.
                </li>
              </ul>
